{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"990e919d-5d7e-4b25-8827-5d36711839f6","content":"This is a known .NET 10 breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30+), and .NET 10 MAUI's edge-to-edge support means the old platform-specific flag no longer drives layout. The modern fix is to react to **IME window insets** directly.\n\n### 1. Set `adjustResize` in your manifest\n\n**`Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`** — on your `<activity>`:\n```xml\n<activity android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\" ... />\n```\n\n### 2. Listen for keyboard insets in `MainActivity`\n\n**`Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing Android.Views;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        var content = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content);\n        if (content is not null)\n            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new ImeInsetsListener());\n    }\n\n    private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime  = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n            // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset\n            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop,\n                         v.PaddingRight, Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom));\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Layout your chat page normally\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*,Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\" ... />\n\n    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row=\"1\" Padding=\"8\">\n        <Entry Placeholder=\"Type a message...\" HorizontalOptions=\"FillAndExpand\" />\n        <Button Text=\"Send\" Command=\"{Binding SendCommand}\" />\n    </HorizontalStackLayout>\n</Grid>\n```\n\n### Why this works\n\nThe `IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` fires whenever the IME (keyboard) opens or closes. It reads the actual keyboard height from `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` and applies it as bottom padding on the root content view, pushing your entire MAUI layout up — no deprecated APIs involved.\n\n### Tip\n\nIf you also need iOS support, iOS `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` generally handles this already. You can disable MAUI's built-in auto-scroll if it conflicts:\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nKeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();\n#endif\n```\n\nin `MainActivity.OnCreate`, so your insets listener is the sole driver on Android.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1e9d1f0a-f2d3-497d-bcfa-96f868a6e330","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue with keyboard handling in .NET 10. This is a known breaking change — `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated/removed because Android itself deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` in API 30+. In .NET 10 (MAUI), the recommended approach changed.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI evolution.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, you could use:\n```csharp\nApp.Current.On<Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.Android>()\n    .UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize);\n```\n\nBut `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated in Android API 30. .NET MAUI has been moving toward using `WindowInsets` and edge-to-edge rendering. For .NET 10, the recommended approach is to use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` to automatically handle scrolling when the keyboard appears, or to properly manage insets yourself.\n\nFor a chat-style UI where you want the entire layout to resize when the keyboard shows, the current best practice is to set `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` in the AndroidManifest.xml on the activity, then combine that with proper insets handling and `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` or padding adjustments based on keyboard insets. The key is handling this through the manifest configuration rather than relying on the deprecated API. sure, let me think through the actual implementation. For .NET 10, the cleanest approach is to leverage the built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` which handles inset adjustments automatically, though I should verify if that's the right tool or if I need to manually subscribe to `WindowInsetsCompat` changes and adjust the layout's bottom padding when the keyboard appears. Setting up the keyboard insets listener...\n\nThe listener calculates the maximum padding needed between the keyboard and system bars, then applies that to the view's bottom padding. I also need to ensure the manifest includes `adjustResize` on the activity to enable this modern insets-based approach for handling soft input.","outputTokens":2218,"requestId":"3C30:30490E:DAA9B3:1104EC3:6A012C6C"},"id":"821ab37f-dd41-480e-b61f-8743b25f0385","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:10:45.238Z","parentId":"68592404-068b-48d1-89c0-0ff95567e8f4"}
